Nick Lewis - Web Developer, Photographer & Blogger

## Web
Though I have been a programmer for many decades, it wasn't until just after the turn of the Millenium that I became more interested in the Web. I set up my own business to focus on a career as a contractor/freelancer developing web sites and nowadays some of these skills have been adapted to include mobile apps as part of our repetoire!

It is an exciting time to be working in this field, that is for sure.

## Photography
I have worked with press and stock agencies since 2002 covering all manner of topics as a photographer. I love to capture the essence of things, people and places. The image captured a reflection of the way I saw it at that unique moment in time. I am on the constant look out for my next photograph, quite often content enough to capture the moment with whatever camera I have at my disposal. 

## Bringing it all together

My Wife and I are based in the town famed for being the birthplace of modern aviation, Farnborough, England - we are happy to travel far and wide. We deliver a mixture of services and we feel that the web and photography truly compliment eachother. 

Follow the blogs on our website to learn more about what we are up to and to get a feel for our business :-)

title.en-GB: North Wales from Conwy to Beaumaris

body.en-GB:
Over the weekend we travelled up to North Wales to take a recce between Conwy and Beaumaris in Anglesey. Taking in a number of places along the way.

My Wife and our friends are all involved with the local Scout Group here in Farnborough and every year they take them on a summer camp and have been to various locations. This year they will be camping in Snowdonia. So we (several of us) decided to book a weekend up there towards the end of last year which just so happened to be yesterday!

We decided to stay in Oswestry on the borders of England and Wales, so that we could travel along the A5 into Snowdonia, to visit some of the places we had read about online beforehand. Sometimes you just have to see them for yourselves, to get a feel for places and to see what else we could find. Some of our friends had never been to North Wales before. So it turned out to be a real eye opener and the people we me met were so helpful. I think some good discounts were negotiated on bookings, especially whilst diaries are still in need of filling for the summer season!

The weather was very interesting with a mixture of wind, snow, hail, brilliant sunshine but mostly it was curiously dry.

![NIC 1404](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/1ODDWjogK0ASC4u666y44w/81de2d6f22a1c24ef0cd3d1cd0d71d60/NIC_1404.jpg)
**The Town Wall** - The town of Conwys medieval walls were built between 1283 and 1287 as a defensive structure around the town after the towns foundation by King Edward I.

![NIC 1406](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/OzOuqSfVyUEsgWosI8Emo/381bb99784c39b9c66b77bfab2243a03/NIC_1406.jpg)

**Close up detail of the stonework** - The very fact that this wall is as old as it is and has stood the test of time, is proof these structures were built to last.

![NIC 1412](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/5u7cDFbSLuiEkWS4yIqMgq/59b7675ee8b0eb0d793518c02229bb84/NIC_1412.jpg)

**The River Conwy** - We followed the wall down to the riverside where the wind was bracing but the light was fantastic for photography!

![Cottages](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/4G09EM9fxe4MMgIsceAeeg/cd1fc3587dc5fd8e22591403bd847c7a/NIC_1413.jpg)

**Town and the wall** - Looking back over my shoulder to take in the pretty cottages and the defensive wall that has kept them safe for many years. Mind you I would guess the cottages were built much much later, probably in the 1800s.

![NIC 1416](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/47c6td4lIsaKowyeAgEkAa/8935253db178de99eb5f5ac069f1f8cf/NIC_1416.jpg)

**Beaumaris Pier** - I wasn't able to get many more photographs but this was my favourite from the trip for many reasons. I hadn't been to Anglesey since 1981/1982 but the rest of our travelling companions were eager to take the short drive from Conwy, across Thomas Telford's splendid [Menai Bridge][6] onto the island. 

It was for me one of the highlights of the day. Beaumaris is a pretty place but we were wearing thermals, ski jackets, fleeces, scarves, woolly hats, ski gloves, walking boots and many other layers. That wind was brutal and shortly after taking this photo, it began to hail and snow! In fact you can see the storm front gathering and moments before, glorious sunlight highlighted the snowcapped peaks of Snowdon on the horizon. Sadly it vanished under a veil of cloud just in time for this photo!

We did stop for awhile at the [George and Dragon][7] in Beaumaris for some hot drinks. It was a fabulous Pub which must have been udated quite recently but still maintained it's old charm and character. In fact I later read on their [website][7] that it dates back to the 1400s making it one of the oldest Pubs in the whole of Wales.

Afterwards we travelled back onto the mainland and drove into the mountains. It was getting dark and the weather was punishing, so we took it all in from the comfort of our friend's car. It took us a further hour and a half to get back to our hotel in Oswestry, just as the weather was getting really nasty.

More photography planned for the Summer in the Snowdonia area.

##Footnote

We were mostly in and out of the car for this trip, so I took quite a few photos on my phone and shared those to Instagram if you are interested in seeing those? We stopped at Llangollen on the way across to Snowdonia and there is a lot to see and do there. Here are two web links of interest.

* [Horse drawn boats][6]
* [Llangollen Railway][8]

I am [@nickeblewis][9] on Instagram, feel free to follow me there :-)

You can also follow my antics via my Facebook page [Nick Lewis Photography][10]

In between 2003 and 2010 I shot a lot of concerts. I have dug through my archives to share some of the better ones. A lot of these have been published in the National Press including The Times, Guardian, Express and Daily Mail etc etc.
As much as I love exploring the wild side of nature, I absolutely love exploring gardens and capturing their beauty on camera in a variety of ways.

metaDescription.en-GB: As much as I love exploring the wild side of nature, I absolutely love exploring gardens and capturing their beauty on camera in a variety of ways.

body.en-GB: There is nothing better than setting foot in the woodlands around where I live in Hampshire, to hear the crunch of leaves under my feet, the birdsong and to explore. Getting lost is a welcome experience rather than a hindrance. I use a variety of lenses and techniques to capture Nature's marvel and share the better ones here.
"One's destination is never a place, but a new way of seeing things" - Henry Miller once said. I live for that myself and it is most apt of a photographer.

![DSC1714](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/5GZRZ4ImdOqUsACEEqcYqM/3152ecf90daaea67412fcfefe466ab52/_DSC1714.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 24-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 1000, 32mm, f9, 1/80sec* 

It's a wet, cold and utterly autumnal afternoon but we didn't want to let that stop us and we knew that the Hampshire Harvest Festival is on this weekend, so we hopped in the car and drove down there. Sadly the weather seemed to have put off many people, as there were some good things there, just not an awful lot of people compared to normal.

I tend to use auto ISO mode on my camera and generally shoot in aperture priority. So it has been interesting to see how my ISO performs, as today it varied quite dramatically but the end results are none the worse off for it. The above shot could have been shot in ISO 100 for all I know, it remains crisp and well detailed.

Sounds like I am writing a camera review but I'm not lol!!

Here are a few of the shots I took whilst we dodged the heavy rain showers. The whole event was situated around the Cathedral with a dozen stalls or so.

![DSC1716](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/6xtM11hNjakyO4Skgkiw6Q/59e45573a0b8b2b92fdafb0a5825a76e/_DSC1716.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 24-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 250, 24mm, f9, 1/60sec* 

Many of the images here have had very little post production applied to them but in this case I did use a Lightroom profile on some of the images to boost them a tiny bit,not really necessary but I fancied trying it out. If anyone is interested, I may write some articles on my tecnhiques.

![DSC1721](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/1gUzcRRcZUIQ84QyymAIW4/7c967a36736be1b3d39b3d89ca5fee03/_DSC1721.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 24-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 1250, 49mm, f9, 1/100sec* 

![DSC1728](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/1TE5MYTXkEG8oeW6wmOWyo/c8498f7e500df54d8dc008975abf6b01/_DSC1728.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 24-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 320, 57mm, f5.6, 1/125sec* 

I used a radial brush on the eyes of the owl because of the low light, they seemed underexposed but were the sharpest point. A little boost made all the difference in LR.

![DSC1736](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/5SxwiobGU0UOSGmgoaMgc6/f51b4c0190b6c41773dd69893c631c57/_DSC1736.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 24-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 500, 44mm, f5.6, 1/100sec* 

![DSC1738](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/6ztZiap0WIEGCgKoCC8iqa/129e3ea072b587774aef6f24e8453d8d/_DSC1738.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 24-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 800, 24mm, f8, 1/60sec* 

![DSC1740](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/4zREVPVopyQwqeOCyUEQ8g/d9032dace971dba3d3928717638fdc48/_DSC1740.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 24-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 500, 24mm, f8, 1/60sec* 

What kind of camera strap do you prefer? I am not a fan of the regular straps you get with your camera, though there is nothing wrong with my Sony strap but I tend to find no matter what, they get in the way and I never wear my camera around my neck. I tend to scrunch up the normal strap around my wrist which is never ideal. So I decided to pop into the London Camera Exchange shop in Winchester and picked up one of these.

The wrist strap is made of a strong neoprene style material which is adjustable and can be quickly released from the camera when not needed. It cost just a tenner. I used it today and I feel a lot more comfortable using it.

![DSC1123](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/2dLv48LQ9W0W4i4U0MOIs/e3adbffdd7bedda53793c57ecf08bbd8/_DSC1123.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 30-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 200, 81mm, f10, 1/20sec - tripod mounted* 

Capital cities are fascinating places, they have their landmarks, their popular cultural highlights, hustle, bustle, heat, action, imagery, fashion, beauty, food, vibe, humour and their dark sides too. So when we visited Rome for a week recently, we kind of did our own thing. Sure enough the guide book was handy but I seldom found myself looking all that much at it. Tina and I prefer to let our eyes, noses, ears, mind and soul lead us. Rome has kind of infected me in a good way, going through the massive number of images we both captured, there has got to be more to see when we go next time.

I am going to kick off with a bunch of street images in this blog post. Yes I have got photos of the Colloseum, The Pantheon, plenty in fact but as a photographer, I plead to be different, it is all part of the challenge that I relish so, so much. 

![DSC0993-3](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/3GbEOjt3bWS6OoyEoCem8w/78ecb8623f0863773b84b075609eb5c1/_DSC0993-3.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 30-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 160, 75mm, f4, 1/160sec* 

I can recall when I purchased the Sony Alpha earlier this Summer, I was looking forward to using it in Rome, for a friends wedding when we returned (though I wasn't the official photographer this time round) and for a helicopter flight last weekend. Yep, all of those things I knew it would be great for and by jove, it has not failed to impress. The lightning fast auto-focus has proved to be reliable and the colour handling of the sensor has really pleased me. I nail my shots far better and spend less time on them in post-production. It is a real keeper of a camera. 

I have so much to share and bring to the pages of this site, should keep me quiet for some time and hopefully you the reader engaged!

![DSC1155](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/294LpJeDJWWuECCEA0my0o/92ebb69d146bacabb78668875427a3b0/_DSC1155.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 30-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 250, 30mm, f5.6, 1/60sec* 

Well, you have to look out for those vehicle parked against a worn out old wall kindof shots don't you? The travel industry love them and I surely will put these all up on Alamy when I get the chance to do so. We had just found Campo de Fiori, the famous market square and I've got photos of that to share at a later point.

![DSC1287](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/XJ55IITvuSK2OAYEeAA42/69237fee0073d22c41fa5082e3123e98/_DSC1287.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 30-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 400, 39mm, f7.1, 1/80sec* 

We had some rain the night before so Rome was nicely saturated on this morning as we walked down towards the centre of the City. I loved this street, it was a bit windy and held loads of interest along the way. I have always loved the Piaggio Ape vans and first came across them down in the South of Italy over a decade ago when we first visited Sorrento. 

![DSC1155](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/294LpJeDJWWuECCEA0my0o/92ebb69d146bacabb78668875427a3b0/_DSC1155.jpg)

*Sony a7R3 - 30-105mm f4 G OSS - ISO 400, 51mm, f7.1, 1/125sec* 

Converted this image in Lightroom CC to Adobe Monochrome and that was it, no other manipulations of the shot at all. I think this is a prime example of using AFS-S on the Sony, picking the focus point, in this case the shop front and then I waited for passers by and I really wanted a scooter! The focus didn't get mixed up, it held on and I am happy with the overall balance that it delivered.

title.en-GB: Casting my mind back to the Summer

body.en-GB:
Now one of the things I love about Winter are the long dark evenings when we are stuck indoors! No I am not trying to be ironic or funny but it is a great time to review those longer days, the evenings where you have seemingly all of the time in the World to get out and explore your local county.

These photos were all taken back in June and all of them were captured during my first proper outing with the Sony A7RIII Mirrorless, Full-Frame camera. I can remember that balmy evening well and I decided to take a trip to our own stretch of Hampshire coastline, where the River Meon meets the Solent. The stretch of beach between Meon Shore and Titchfield. 

I have to say it is one of my favourite locations and it is within an hour from home. It has plenty of variety to offer, as these photos I hope show...

![DSC00015](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/5mvL9m4SOsCuc24qCc4Iky/6d44d7e0de8a7d1ad776c398c4edc30d/DSC00015.jpg) 

I did crop this photo a bit to focus more on the Black-Headed Gull. The original showed more of the harbour wall just beyond. The images that come off this camera are massive and cropping aggressively seems to have no detrimental effect on the quality of the image, there are plenty of pixels packed in!

![DSC00038](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/6KGe61vDpuUCWEUw6eoKYI/0fb5a35ec73ef837ec82a4d2a4da64d3/DSC00038.jpg) 

If you know me well, I have a thing for beachuts and boats for that matter! They are not easy subjects to capture without being overly cliched, so I tend to go for wonky angles, abstracts and since these huts were a fairly bland colour, a conversion to B&W works well.

![DSC00053](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/37vZ5Q7R5K6iAi8UgYuOcE/1a30625a1ebfeef013e5fdfa3e28b30c/DSC00053.jpg) 

This photo was so funny. I was originally taking a photo of the breakwaters and it wasn't really working for me. I thought about it a bit more, thought again but it just wasn't looking that great a composition.

Then this dog appeared from nowhere, bearing in mind I was looking through my viewfinder, wondering around trying to square something up in the frame. He posed for a about allof 3 seconds, I took this shot and as if to express his feelings towards my photo - cocked his leg against one of the posts!

His owners caught up with him, saw what had happened, I was in fits of laughter as were they!!

![DSC00079](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/nPKsQyyYJqmCmYQ68A4UU/7f165a062f35cbc0b6e5ac389d9a8eba/DSC00079.jpg) 

This chap was too engrossed in what he was doing to notice me taking a photo of his boat. Luckily he didn't take a wee...

![DSC00060](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/1BkOQDHhwsOC6wmc2ygiUo/2449e0ae3744eaa4fbff6cf1c0fa5ff7/DSC00060.jpg) 

I was following these people along, well not literally otherwise that would be a bit freaky! Then the bursts of sunlight and the shadows they were casting just clicked in my head.... and so did my shutter!

![DSC00073](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/2uYhfgZ1CcWuKQc0m6sOeA/00c7e52039321fbae67ccad6ce937cd2/DSC00073.jpg)

More boats and I loved the one called Squirrel, though it left me wondering why a boat should be named after an animal that spends it's days up trees, looking after it's nuts most of the time...

![DSC00044](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/2JRdXUiDjao4WWUIm8eqyK/bd639ed4f6ba110e50cfb8bcc38791a2/DSC00044.jpg) 

Like Pebbles on a beach, kicked around, displaced by feet, oh like broken stones - wrote Paul Weller in one of his songs...

![DSC00086](//images.ctfassets.net/5kdxu849wo7r/4RQUf6mIcgSqG0o02WQqqK/bbc2cea8eda91daa48133b3acd0f27f1/DSC00086.jpg) 

The odd one out in this collection, as I took it on the way home. The twilight sky was fascinating and I decided to pull over, leave my headlights on and take this picture. I thought it was pretty cool :-)

## Grey and dismal outside? Stay indoors?
You know those grey days that are lacking in soul and above all else that key ingredient in photography... light? Well, you stay indoors do you not? I beg to differ and you might be persuaded to think again, for there is no such thing as "bad light", there is always something you can photograph, no matter what!

## Take the grey challenge!
Today was a case in point for me. It was very grey, the light levels were low, there was a feint drizzle in the air, it was fairly cold but I was determined to give it a go. However I didn't want to waste too much time driving around looking for locations, so I had one or two in mind that aren't far from where we are based.

I have for some time quite liked the idea of photographing a particular subject over the course of a year, the River Wey being one of them. So this may be the start of something, perhaps a gallery of sorts... anyway I chose to head for Waverley Abbey and the river Wey passes close by. There is a small car park by a rather interesting WWII Pill Box with a beautiful Oak tree smack bang in the middle, so parking is a bit awkward there. 

A path leads down the edge of the river towards the abbey and on the other side of the River is Waverley Abbey House, a rather grand looking building in itself.

### Breaking down the shot
I took this shot handheld and as I walked along the river bank, this shot presented itself. I was drawn to the serenity, something reminded me of Ansel Adams, one of my all time favourite photographers. The composition dead simple, muted colours, a strong reflection and water that practically looked like a sheet of glass.

### The Gallery
I will add these to one of the main galleries eventually and currently devising a system to follow when it comes to such things. I may end up with a bunch of galleries based on topic or the other options would be to have a bunch of areas/locations etc. Who knows, a website evolves over time and perhaps it's best not to overthink, to just allow the business and the site to grow organically.

I am looking at ways of integrating a payment system into this site, to sell prints and e-cards of my photos.

### No comments? Will I be able to comment?
I am thinking about this at the moment, in the sense that I like the idea of discussion on social media rather than comments locked away within the site. If I do add comments to this site, I will use Disqus, but that is a job for another day!

title.en-GB: How to choose a printing lab for your online photography store

body.en-GB:
I am in the process of developing an online shop to sell my own photographic art work. So I see this as a series of stages, that can be broken down as follows:

- Pick a photo to use as the guinea pig
- Shortlist some printing laboratory firms - how many should I whittle it down to? Location, does it matter?
- What size shall I choose?
- Test out the upload process to each of these firms, which is the easiest? Best featured?
- How do they compare for price? Do I set a budget on this experiment?
- How well packaged and presented are the prints when they arrive?
- How good is the reproduction of the chosen image?
- How good is the quality of the product?
- Can I just print myself? Well I could but that is something I plan to do later, further down the line
- Finally I will be selling the prints on at a discounted price! Let me know if you are interested and we shall work out the maths later!

## The shortlisted images

In the gallery below, I have selected 15 potential images for my print lab test, please help me choose the one to send off. I will then use the selected image for the laboratory test!

Check back again soon to learn what happens next...
